542 public:
543 /** The key of the object (data) being protected. */

545 /**
546 Read-write lock protecting this lock context.
547
548 @note The fact that we use read-write lock prefers readers here is
549 important as deadlock detector won't work correctly otherwise.
550
551 For example, imagine that we have following waiters graph:
552
553 ctxA -> obj1 -> ctxB -> obj1 -|
554 ^ |
555 |----------------------------|
556
557 and both ctxA and ctxB start deadlock detection process:
558
559 ctxA read-locks obj1 ctxB read-locks obj2
560 ctxA goes deeper ctxB goes deeper
561
562 Now ctxC comes in who wants to start waiting on obj1, also
563 ctxD comes in who wants to start waiting on obj2.
564
565 ctxC tries to write-lock obj1 ctxD tries to write-lock obj2
566 ctxC is blocked ctxD is blocked
567
568 Now ctxA and ctxB resume their search:
569
570 ctxA tries to read-lock obj2 ctxB tries to read-lock obj1
571
572 If m_rwlock prefers writes (or fair) both ctxA and ctxB would be
573 blocked because of pending write locks from ctxD and ctxC
574 correspondingly. Thus we will get a deadlock in deadlock detector.
575 If m_wrlock prefers readers (actually ignoring pending writers is
576 enough) ctxA and ctxB will continue and no deadlock will occur.
577 */
578 mysql_prlock_t m_rwlock;

698 /**
699 @returns "Fast path" increment for request for "unobtrusive" type
700 of lock, 0 - if it is request for "obtrusive" type of
701 lock.
702
703 @note We split all lock types for each of MDL namespaces
704 in two sets:
705
706 A) "unobtrusive" lock types
707 1) Each type from this set should be compatible with all other
708 types from the set (including itself).
709 2) These types should be common for DML operations
710
711 Our goal is to optimize acquisition and release of locks of this
712 type by avoiding complex checks and manipulations on m_waiting/
713 m_granted bitmaps/lists. We replace them with a check of and
714 increment/decrement of integer counters.
715 We call the latter type of acquisition/release "fast path".
716 Use of "fast path" reduces the size of critical section associated
717 with MDL_lock::m_rwlock lock in the common case and thus increases
718 scalability.
719
720 The amount by which acquisition/release of specific type
721 "unobtrusive" lock increases/decreases packed counter in
722 MDL_lock::m_fast_path_state is returned by this function.
723
724 B) "obtrusive" lock types
725 1) Granted or pending lock of those type is incompatible with
726 some other types of locks or with itself.
727 2) Not common for DML operations
728
729 These locks have to be always acquired involving manipulations on
730 m_waiting/m_granted bitmaps/lists, i.e. we have to use "slow path"
731 for them. Moreover in the presence of active/pending locks from
732 "obtrusive" set we have to acquire using "slow path" even locks of
733 "unobtrusive" type.
734
735 @see MDL_scoped_lock::m_unobtrusive_lock_increment and
736 @see MDL_object_lock::m_unobtrusive_lock_increment for
737 definitions of these sets for scoped and per-object locks.
738 */
